y speculative. Environmental interconnection is present, but hydrothermal arginine chemistry is problematic because arginine is thermolabile and black-smoker-like conditions are generally destructive. Literature alignment is mixed: the network captures the field's two main hypotheses and acknowledges speculative gaps, but several reactions should have been downgraded further or represented as availability nodes rather than direct syntheses. Overall this is a useful connected synthesis network for reasoning, but not an approved high-confidence prebiotic synthesis network for arginine.\",\n  \"approved\": false,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.84,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.81\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_003": 0.15, "rxn_004": 0.55, "rxn_006": 0.85, "rxn_007": 0.9, "rxn_008": 0.7, "rxn_009": 0.8, "rxn_010": 0.7}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.66, "pathway_coherence": 0.82, "environmental_progression": 0.84, "target_achievement": 0.68, "overall_confidence": 0.72, "feedback": "This is the most literature-aligned pathway in the network because it follows the Patel/Sutherland cyanosulfidic precursor logic: acrylonitrile, beta-aminopropionitrile, beta-aminopropionaldehyde, cyanamide-mediated guanylation, and progression to an arginine precursor followed by hydrolysis. However, the first step is weak: NH3 -> HCN is not an adequate prebiotic representation of HCN formation from reduced atmospheric mixtures. The later conversion from the precursor ensemble to arginine is plausible only as a hydrolysis of an aminonitrile precursor and remains incompletely specified. Overall, good coherence but only moderate confidence because the complete simple-feedstock-to-arginine sequence has not been experimentally demonstrated.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_010"], "suggestions": ["Replace the oversimplified NH3-only HCN formation with a literature-grounded reduced-gas photochemical or discharge sourc