erature itself proposes this urea-cycle-like branch (Juarez et al., 2021; Ferris et al., 1978).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative conversion of citrulline to arginine via cyanamide-mediated guanyl transfer network\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool; hypothetical urea-cycle analog branch\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Citrulline in a cyanamide-rich network is represented as a late-stage entry to arginine, standing in for unresolved prebiotic equivalents of biological argininosuccinate chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"No direct experimental demonstration exists for a prebiotic citrulline-to-arginine conversion. This node is intentionally labeled speculative and retained only because the deep research report identifies a prebiotic urea-cycle analog as a proposed but unproven route; the network therefore acknowledges the gap rather than hiding it (Cunin et al., 1986; Juarez et al., 2021; Ferris et al., 1978).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Availability of ornithine from spark-discharge and meteoritic input\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration after atmospheric synthesis/exogenous delivery\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"represents deposition and concentration in evaporitic or volcanic pool settings rather than a single-step synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ornithine produced elsewhere in atmospheric discharge chemistry or delivered exogenously is concentrated into reactive surface pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Previous attempts overreached by inventing direct ornithine synthesis. Here ornithine is introduced only as an availability node grounded in actual detections from spark discharge and tentative meteoritic evidence, with minerals serving concentration/protection roles rather than fictive synthesis catalysts (Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011; Meierhenrich et al., 2004; Catalano et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Availability of glutamic acid from established prebiotic sources\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration after atmospheric or meteoritic input\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"represents known prebiotic abundance rather than a direct one-step surface synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glutamic acid from atmospheric synthesis or exogenous input is accumulated in surface reservoirs.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glutamate is a well-established prebiotic amino acid, but no credible direct conversion to ornithine is claimed here. This molecule is included to represent the literature's recognition that glutamate is the biosynthetic source of arginine in biology and a likely available prebiotic pool component (Johnson et al., 2008; Naraoka et al., 2023; Higgs & Pudritz, 2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Trace arginine formation under supercritical CO2/H2O from pyruvate and hydroxylamine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \">73 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"supercritical CO2/H2O; arginine detected after acid hydrolysis; trace yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex multistep chemistry in supercritical CO2/H2O involving pyruvate and hydroxylamine generated trace arginine among hydrolysis products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the only reported abiotic experimental detection of arginine, but it is trace, mechanistically unresolved, and depends on intermediate feedstocks rather than simple starting materials. It is therefore retained as a low-confidence empirical route and not elevated above the cyanamide/ornithine or cyanosulfidic branches (Fujioka et al., 2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface availability of hydroxylamine for the Fujioka branch\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"photochemical redox on mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic UV-exposed pool; included only to supply the Fujioka feedstock\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrogen redox photochemistry in shallow mineral-rich settings provides hydroxylamine as a reactive nitrogen intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydroxylamine is not the central literature route to arginine, but the Fujioka experiment requires it; this node is included only to connect that empirical branch and is subordinate to the main cyanamide-based chemistry (Fujioka et al., 2009; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic arginine-aminonitrile route\",\n      \"description\": \"Best-supported literature pathway from HCN and acetylene through acrylonitrile, beta-aminopropionitrile, beta-aminopropionaldehyde, cyanamide guanylation, arginine aminonitrile precursor, then hydrolysis to arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanamide-primed cyanosulfidic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Same as P1 but explicitly sourcing cyanamide photochemically before the guanylation branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct ornithine guanylation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Historically demonstrated two-phase route: ornithine availability followed by direct guanylation with cyanamide to yield arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_015\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Ornithine guanylation with independent cyanamide sourcing and clay concentration\",\n      \"description\": \"Variant of direct ornithine guanylation emphasizing separate surface generation of cyanamide and concentration of ornithine in reactive pools.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomer-citrulline branch to arginine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hypothetical urea-cycle-like branch in which HCN oligomer hydrolysis furnishes citrulline-containing pools and cyanamide-rich chemistry gives arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Ornithine to citrulline to arginine branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Hypothetical carbamoylation of ornithine by cyanate to citrulline, then unresolved late conversion to arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_015\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical cyanosulfidic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Cross-environment route in which hydrothermal reduced carbon supports broader prebiotic inventories feeding surface cyanosulfidic chemistry, culminating in arginine aminonitrile hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate branch to trace arginine\",\n      \"description\": \"Low-confidence empirical branch connecting hydrothermal pyruvate provisioning to the Fujioka supercritical CO2/H2O experiment.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Guanidine-rich surface variant feeding arginine chemistry\",\n      \"description\": \"Variant route emphasizing shared HCN pool chemistry generating guanidine and cyanamide alongside the main arginine precursor network, illustrating nitrogen-rich convergence in the same environment.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Glutamate-availability scaffold converging on ornithine-first arginine synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"Conceptual evolutionary scaffold acknowledging glutamate abundance and ornithine-first logic without claiming unsupported direct glutamate-to-ornithine conversion; arginine still forms via direct ornithine guanylation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_007\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Arginine", "overall_strategy": "This network is literature-constrained and explicitly reflects that arginine is not established as a robust direct product of simple prebiotic feedstocks. The strategy therefore uses a two-phase assembly centered on the best-supported chemistry: (i) generation and concentration of key C3/C5 and guanylating precursors across hydrothermal and surface settings, especially cyanamide, acrylonitrile-derived nitriles, ornithine, citrulline, and guanidino aminonitrile intermediates; and (ii) final arginine formation by hydrolysis or guanylation in prebiotic pool settings. Hydrothermal chemistry is used conservatively to supply reducing power and simple carbon intermediates, while destructive high-temperature black-smoker chemistry is avoided for arginine itself. Surface cyanosulfidic chemistry follows Patel et al. (2015) and Tsanakopoulou & Sutherland (2017), and direct ornithine guanylation follows Schulze & Winterstein (1899) with prebiotic plausibility from cyanamide availability. Additional branches are flagged as speculative where the literature identifies them as hypothetical, including cyanate/citrulline and the Fujioka supercritical route. The 10 listed pathways are route variants through the same connected bipartite network, not 10 independently demonstrated laboratory syntheses.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3