stocks are themselves nontrivial. This branch should remain clearly secondary.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_017\",\n        \"rxn_018\",\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Keep this branch explicitly labeled as low-confidence literature outlier\",\n        \"Do not allow this route to materially influence overall target-achievement claims\",\n        \"Clarify hydroxylamine provenance and note unresolved mechanism\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.8,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.92,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.86\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n      \"feedback\": \"This variant benefits from the strong literature support for guanidine formation in irradiated ammonium cyanide solutions. Guanidine is relevant to arginine chemistry broadly, though it is not the principal guanylating species in the canonical arginine-aminonitrile route, where cyanamide is more central. As a guanidine-rich context feeding the same cyanosulfidic branch, the pathway is plausible but somewhat less direct than P1.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Clarify whether guanidine is a side-pool species or a direct participant in target-forming steps\",\n        \"Avoid conflating guanidine availability with direct arginine synthesis\",\n        \"Maintain cyanamide as the principal guanylating node for target production\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.7,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.82\n      },\n 