ioka's trace arginine experiment (Kitadai, 2015; Amend & Shock, 1998; Fujioka et al., 2009)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Photochemical cyanamide formation", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 with phosphate-buffered shallow pool", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated anaerobic surface environment; reduced-gas photochemistry representation"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven nitrile/nitrene chemistry in reduced atmospheres and shallow pools yields cyanamide, stabilized and buffered in phosphate-rich settings.", "reasoning": "Cyanamide has strong prebiotic support from photochemistry of reduced gas mixtures and is a central node in cyanosulfidic chemistry; exact one-step aqueous generation from HCN plus NH3 is used here as a network connector and should be regarded as a simplified availability step rather than a fully demonstrated single reaction (Schimpl, Lemmon & Calvin, 1965; Patel et al., 2015; Powner, Gerland & Sutherland, 2009)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "UV ammonium cyanide photochemistry to guanidine", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "iron-assisted UV photolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "254 nm UV; pH 8.4-8.5; 7 days to 10 weeks; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Photolysis of ammonium cyanide solutions reorganizes CN-derived nitrogen chemistry to guanidine.", "reasoning": "Lohrmann showed guanidine formation in 8-20% yield from ammonium cyanide under UV with iron catalyst; guanidine is kinetically stable and relevant as a guanidinium-source node, though not itself a demonstrated efficient arginine precursor in one pot (Lohrmann, 1972; Robertson & Miller, 1995)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanosulfidic cross-coupling to acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox system in phosphate buffer on sulfide-rich mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "35C; UV light; anaerobic cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Cu-mediated photoredox cross-coupling of HCN-derived species with acetylene gives acrylonitrile in a cyanosulfidic network.", "reasoning": "This is the entry reaction explicitly drawn from the Sutherland cyanosulfidic protometabolism network under 35C anaerobic UV conditions with phosphate and sulfide chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Tsanakopoulou & Sutherland, 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Acrylonitrile aminolysis to beta-aminopropionitrile", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "cyanosulfidic aqueous medium with phosphate", "aqueous": "true", "other": "35C; anaerobic; UV-compatible surface pool chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia adds across the activated nitrile-bearing alkene to form beta-aminopropionitrile.", "reasoning": "This transformation is part of the arginine-precursor branch described in the cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework (Patel et al., 2015; Tsanakopoulou & Sutherland, 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Photoreductive conversion of beta-aminopropionitrile to beta-aminopropionaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_009", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox cyanosulfidic conditions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "35C; anaerobic; H2S-mediated reduction network"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox reduction of the nitrile branch in the presence of sulfur reductant provides the corresponding aldehyde.", "reasoning": "Beta-aminopropionaldehyde is the key branchpoint intermediate identified by Patel and later discussed by Tsanakopoulou & Sutherland; this specific reduction context is embedded within their cyanosulfidic network rather than a standalone classic reduction protocol (Patel et al., 2015; Tsanakopoulou & Sutherland, 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Guanylation of beta-aminopropionaldehyde by cyanamide", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration in shallow pool", "aqueous": "true", "other": "35C; anaerobic; surface concentration-enhanced guanylation"}, "mechanism": "Primary amine attacks the electrophilic carbon of cyanamide to form a guanidino-substituted aldehyde.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. specifically describe the reaction of beta-aminopropionaldehyde with cyanamide as especially efficient in the arginine/proline precursor branch; montmorillonite is included as a plausible concentrating mineral without claiming it was used in that paper (Patel et al., 2015; Tsanakopoulou & Sutherland, 2017; Catalano et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Photoreduction and cyanide homologation to arginine aminonitrile precursor", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox cyanosulfidic network", "aqueous": "true", "other": "35C; anaerobic; H2S/Cu-photochemistry context"}, "mechanism": "Sequential photoreduction and HCN addition install the alpha-aminonitrile functionality, yielding the compound 46-type arginine precursor.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. infer production of compound 46, the alpha-aminonitrile precursor of arginine, from the especially efficient cyanamide capture step; Tsanakopoulou & Sutherland confirmed this precursor logic, though quantitative isolated yields to arginine were not reported (Patel et al., 2015; Tsanakopoulou & Sutherland, 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrolysis of arginine aminonitrile precursor to arginine", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous hydrolysis in pools or interfaces; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Nitrile hydrolysis converts the alpha-aminonitrile precursor into the corresponding alpha-amino acid arginine.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is standard in Strecker-derived prebiotic chemistry, and this step is the literature-proposed endpoint for the Patel/Sutherland arginine precursor branch; however, a fully continuous simple-feedstock-to-arginine experiment has not been demonstrated, so this remains an inferred completion step (Patel et al., 2015; Tsanakopoulou & Sutherland, 2017; Miller & Orgel, 1974)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Ornithine availability from spark-discharge and meteoritic inventory", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface concentration after atmospheric synthesis/deposition", "aqueous": "true", "other": "represented as environmental availability node rather than a claimed single mechanistic step"}, "mechanism": "Atmospheric discharge or exogenous delivery supplies ornithine to surface pools where minerals concentrate it.", "reasoning": "This is intentionally encoded as an availability/concentration node, not a claim of direct one-step synthesis from HCN and NH3. Ornithine is documented in Miller volcanic spark-discharge reanalyses and tentatively in Murchison; montmorillonite provides plausible concentration after delivery (Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011; Meierhenrich et al., 2004; Catalano et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Direct guanylation of ornithine by cyanamide to arginine", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous guanylation; conceptually related to Ba(OH)2-promoted or Lewis-acid-catalyzed modern demonstrations; prebiotic mineral concentration plausible"}, "mechanism": "The terminal primary amine of ornithine attacks cyanamide to form the guanidinium side chain of arginine.", "reasoning": "This is the most direct literature-supported conceptual route to arginine: Schulze & Winterstein first demonstrated ornithine guanylation by cyanamide, and Tsubokura et al. later showed aqueous cyanamide guanylation can be very efficient, though not under strictly prebiotic catalyst systems. It remains prebiotically plausible but not experimentally closed from simple feedstocks (Schulze & Winterstein, 1899; Tsubokura et al., 2014; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Montmorillonite-mediated concentration and protection of arginine", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite interlayer adsorption", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 5-7; wet-dry cycles possible"}, "mechanism": "Cation exchange adsorbs guanidinium-bearing arginine into clay interlayers, concentrating and protecting it.", "reasoning": "Catalano et al. showed montmorillonite selectively adsorbs arginine and lysine much more strongly than neutral amino acids, providing a plausible concentration/protection step after any low-yield arginine-forming process (Catalano et al., 2024; Zhou et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Cyanate carbamoylation of ornithine to citrulline", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface concentration with phosphate buffering", "aqueous": "true", "other": "hypothetical prebiotic urea-cycle analog"}, "mechanism": "The terminal amine of ornithine reacts with cyanate to form a ureido side chain, generating citrulline.", "reasoning": "Cyanate has been proposed as a prebiotic carbamoyl donor more stable than carbamoyl phosphate, and citrulline has precedent in HCN oligomer hydrolysates. This branch is retained explicitly as hypothetical because no continuous prebiotic ornithine-to-arginine urea-cycle analogue has been demonstrated (Ferris et al., 1978; Juarez et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "HCN oligomer hydrolysis contribution to citrulline inventory", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-assisted HCN oligomerization followed by hydrolysis on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "shallow pool; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "HCN oligomerization followed by hydrolytic rearrangement yields a complex mixture that can include citrulline.", "reasoning": "Ferris et al. reported citrulline among products identified in HCN oligomer hydrolysates. This reaction is included as a low-specificity source of citrulline inventory rather than a selective synthesis (Ferris et al., 1978)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Trace supercritical CO2/H2O arginine formation from pyruvate and hydroxylamine", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "333K", "pressure": ">73 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "supercritical CO2/H2O; arginine detected only after acid hydrolysis; trace yield"}, "mechanism": "Unresolved multistep condensation/rearrangement chemistry under supercritical CO2/H2O gives trace arginine after hydrolysis.", "reasoning": "Fujioka et al. reported 0.32 micromol arginine from hydroxylamine hydrochloride and pyruvic acid under supercritical CO2/H2O, but the mechanism is unresolved and the route is weak relative to other branches; it is included only because it is one of the few direct abiotic arginine detections in the literature (Fujioka et al., 2009)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Hydrothermal-context glutamate availability", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "323-373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "iron-sulfur/iron-oxide mineral assemblage", "aqueous": "true", "other": "vent-ocean mixing interface; thermodynamic context only"}, "mechanism": "Reduced hydrothermal environments can thermodynamically favor amino-acid synthesis, allowing glutamate to serve as a conceptual biosynthetic precursor pool.", "reasoning": "This is included as a thermodynamic/context node rather than a specific demonstrated one-step synthesis; glutamate is widely observed in prebiotic experiments and meteorites, and hydrothermal calculations support amino-acid favorability near vent interfaces (Amend & Shock, 1998; Kitadai, 2015; Naraoka et al., 2023)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical cyanosulfidic arginine-aminonitrile pathway", "description": "The literature-strongest route from the Sutherland network: acrylonitrile formation, aminonitrile branch growth, cyanamide guanylation, compound-46-type precursor formation, and hydrolysis to arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Direct ornithine-cyanamide guanylation", "description": "The classic two-phase strategy where prebiotically available ornithine meets cyanamide in aqueous settings to furnish arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_003", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_016", "mol_007"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Ornithine guanylation with clay protection", "description": "Direct ornithine guanylation followed by montmorillonite adsorption to concentrate and preserve low-yield arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_003", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_016", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal-carbon to cyanosulfidic precursor route", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced-carbon supply links vent chemistry to surface cyanosulfidic arginine precursor formation and final hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_020", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Cyanamide-rich direct route", "description": "Surface photochemical formation of cyanamide converges with environmentally available ornithine to give arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Cyanosulfidic route with post-formation clay capture", "description": "The Patel-Tsanakopoulou precursor route followed by montmorillonite adsorption of formed arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "HCN-oligomer citrulline branch feeding arginine problem space", "description": "A hypothetical branch where HCN oligomer hydrolysis yields citrulline, representing a prebiotic urea-cycle analog precursor pool connected to arginine chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_015", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_018", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Ornithine to citrulline analog branch", "description": "Hypothetical carbamoylation of ornithine by cyanate to citrulline, retained as a literature-discussed but unproven analog branch connected to the target landscape.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_016", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Trace supercritical CO2/H2O route", "description": "The sole direct abiotic arginine detection reported from pyruvate and hydroxylamine under supercritical CO2/H2O conditions.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_020", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Mixed ornithine-cyanamide route with hydrothermal support", "description": "Hydrothermal amino-acid context supports precursor availability, while surface ornithine and cyanamide converge in the biochemically plausible guanylation step.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_017", "rxn_011", "rxn_003", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_019", "mol_016", "mol_007"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_005", "mol_007", "mol_016", "mol_014", "mol_020"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_007", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_016", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_012", "rxn_014"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_015", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_016"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_013"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_005", "incoming_reactions": [], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004